description: From French julienne (1722), from given name Jules or Julien, presumably from an otherwise unknown chef of that name. Originally used in potage julienne (“Julienne potage, soup in the manner of Jules/Julien”), meaning “soup made from thin slices”; this sense is now known as chiffonade.

entries.meaning: (cooking) A garnish of vegetables cut into long, thin strips.

verbs.description: julienne (third-person singular simple present juliennes, present participle julienning, simple past and past participle julienned)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To prepare by cutting in this way.
